<div id="review_786366006" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/786366006" />
    <a title="Ellis Knox" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3338358-ellis-knox"><img alt="Ellis Knox" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501601345p2/3338358.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/786366006?book_show_action=true">Aug 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ellis Knox" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ellis Knox" href="/user/show/3338358-ellis-knox">Ellis Knox</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3338358-ellis-knox?shelf=sf">sf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer786366006" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6555793278709720099">I read the Foundation trilogy back in 1966. Found all three in a single hardcover, used, in a box in the back of a Portland bookstore on 4th Street. Fifty cents. Whaddadeal.<br/><br/>I knew Asimov had published other Foundation books but I was never interested. Now, at the other end of my life, I figured I owed the maestro at least one more read.<br/><br/>I enjoyed the early parts of the book. One premise that I enjoyed was trying to find Earth. Or, rather, how a civilization in which Earth was no more than a hundr</span>
  <span id="freeText6555793278709720099" style="display:none">I read the Foundation trilogy back in 1966. Found all three in a single hardcover, used, in a box in the back of a Portland bookstore on 4th Street. Fifty cents. Whaddadeal.<br /><br />I knew Asimov had published other Foundation books but I was never interested. Now, at the other end of my life, I figured I owed the maestro at least one more read.<br /><br />I enjoyed the early parts of the book. One premise that I enjoyed was trying to find Earth. Or, rather, how a civilization in which Earth was no more than a hundred variant myths scattered across the galaxy. How would one even start? So that was fun.<br /><br />But nearly the entire book is a series of dialogs. A character would put forward a proposition, which would be countered by another. There follows every possible variation, with varying counters, until at the end of the chapter a decision was reached to take an action.<br /><br />Some individual characters were mildly interesting, but not much more, for Asimov keeps everyone within a pretty narrow emotional range. His handling of females is notoriously bad, but it's been so long since I've read him, that angle struck me hard.<br /><br />In short, this is a cerebral novel pretty obviously meant to patch in a narrative gap in his overall Foundation world. I'm glad I read it, but I think I can leave my memories of other Asimov classics intact, if somewhat dusty.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6555793278709720099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

